'''Kawasuso Shrine''' (川濯神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社}} located in {{ill|Nesaki Town|ja|根崎町}}, {{ill|Hakodate City|ja|函館市}}, {{ill|Hokkaido|ja|北海道}}. Its former {{ill|typeing System|ja|近代社格制度|1=Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines}} classification is that of a village shrine.
== Overview == The shrine stands on a {{ill|marine terrace|ja|海岸段丘}} on the east bank of the {{ill|Nesaki Miya River|ja|根崎宮の川}}. It was established and enshrined at its current location in {{ill|1664|ja|1664th year}} ({{ill|Kanbun|ja|寛文}} 4). In {{ill|1903|ja|1903rd year}} ({{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era}} 36), the {{ill|shrine architecture|ja|神社建築}} was renovated. After a period without a building, it was reconstructed in {{ill|1937|ja|1937th year}} (Showa 12) at another location and moved to its current site in {{ill|1967|ja|1967th year}} (Showa 42). According to tradition, fishermen in the area once used the trees within the shrine precincts as landmarks for fishing. The main hall is built in the {{ill|Gongen-zukuri|ja|権現造}} style.<ref>函館市史 銭亀沢編 p377-378</ref><ref name="jinjyacho">[https://hokkaidojinjacho.jp/%E5%B7%9D%E6%BF%AF%E7%A5%9E%E7%A4%BE-2/ 『川濯神社』] 北海道神社庁, accessed October 21, 2023</ref><ref name="zenigamezawahen_302">函館市史 銭亀沢編 p302</ref>
On {{ill|August 29|ja|1975th year}} (Showa 50), an {{ill|Enkū|ja|円空仏|q=Enkū|lt=Enku Buddha}} carved by the Edo period itinerant monk {{ill|Enkū|ja|円空}} was discovered by Shibuya Michio, an associate professor at the Hakodate National College of Technology.<ref>函館市史 通説編第1巻 p4dd</ref>
== deity == * {{ill|Konohanasakuya-hime|ja|木花開耶姫命|1=Konohanasakuya-hime}}<ref name="jinjyacho" />
== Rituals and Festivals == Shrine festivals are carried out under the leadership of the town council president and the head of the Hōsan Association (representing the {{ill|Ujiko|ja|氏子}}). Since {{ill|1983|ja|1983rd year}} (Showa 58), these positions have been filled by recommendation. Seasonal prayers, such as the Spring and Summer Purifications (Oharai), are performed by priests from the {{ill|Kameda Hachimangu|ja|亀田八幡宮}}. In addition, lucky charms such as {{ill|hamaya|ja|破魔矢}} are supplied by Kameda Hachimangu.<ref name="zenigamezawahen_302" /> * New Year's Visit (Hatsumōde): Ujiko representatives keep watch through the night from {{ill|New Year's Eve|ja|大晦日}} to {{ill|New Year's Day|ja|元旦}}. * Spring Kagura: Around {{ill|February 20|ja|2月20日}} * Spring Purification: Around {{ill|April 20|ja|4月20日}} * Summer Purification (Oharai): Around {{ill|June 20|ja|6月20日}} * Summer Kagura (festival): From {{ill|August 15|ja|8月15日}} to {{ill|August 16|ja|8月16日}}<ref>函館市史 銭亀沢編 p406-408</ref>
