'''Kawasuso Shrine''' (川濯神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Nesaki Town|ja|根崎町|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hakodate City|ja|函館市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Hokkaido|ja|北海道|12=draft|12=draft}}. Its former {{ill|typeing System|ja|近代社格制度|1=Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines|12=draft|12=draft}} classification is that of a village shrine.

== Overview ==
The shrine stands on a {{ill|marine terrace|ja|海岸段丘|12=draft|12=draft}} on the east bank of the {{ill|Nesaki Miya River|ja|根崎宮の川|12=draft|12=draft}}. It was established and enshrined at its current location in {{ill|1664|ja|1664th year|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Kanbun|ja|寛文|12=draft|12=draft}} 4). In {{ill|1903|ja|1903rd year|12=draft|12=draft}} ({{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|12=draft|12=draft}} 36), the {{ill|shrine architecture|ja|神社建築|12=draft|12=draft}} was renovated. After a period without a building, it was reconstructed in {{ill|1937|ja|1937th year|12=draft|12=draft}} (Showa 12) at another location and moved to its current site in {{ill|1967|ja|1967th year|12=draft|12=draft}} (Showa 42). According to tradition, fishermen in the area once used the trees within the shrine precincts as landmarks for fishing. The main hall is built in the {{ill|Gongen-zukuri|ja|権現造|12=draft|12=draft}} style.<ref>函館市史 銭亀沢編 p377-378</ref><ref name="jinjyacho">[https://hokkaidojinjacho.jp/%E5%B7%9D%E6%BF%AF%E7%A5%9E%E7%A4%BE-2/ 『川濯神社』] 北海道神社庁, accessed October 21, 2023</ref><ref name="zenigamezawahen_302">函館市史 銭亀沢編 p302</ref>

On {{ill|August 29|ja|1975th year|12=draft|12=draft}} (Showa 50), an {{ill|Enkū|ja|円空仏|q=Enkū|lt=Enku Buddha|12=draft|12=draft}} carved by the Edo period itinerant monk {{ill|Enkū|ja|円空|12=draft|12=draft}} was discovered by Shibuya Michio, an associate professor at the Hakodate National College of Technology.<ref>函館市史 通説編第1巻 p4dd</ref>

== deity ==
* {{ill|Konohanasakuya-hime|ja|木花開耶姫命|1=Konohanasakuya-hime|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref name="jinjyacho" />

== Rituals and Festivals ==
Shrine festivals are carried out under the leadership of the town council president and the head of the Hōsan Association (representing the {{ill|Ujiko|ja|氏子|12=draft|12=draft}}). Since {{ill|1983|ja|1983rd year|12=draft|12=draft}} (Showa 58), these positions have been filled by recommendation. Seasonal prayers, such as the Spring and Summer Purifications (Oharai), are performed by priests from the {{ill|Kameda Hachimangu|ja|亀田八幡宮|12=draft|12=draft}}. In addition, lucky charms such as {{ill|hamaya|ja|破魔矢|12=draft|12=draft}} are supplied by Kameda Hachimangu.<ref name="zenigamezawahen_302" />
* New Year's Visit (Hatsumōde): Ujiko representatives keep watch through the night from {{ill|New Year's Eve|ja|大晦日|12=draft|12=draft}} to {{ill|New Year's Day|ja|元旦|12=draft|12=draft}}.
* Spring Kagura: Around {{ill|February 20|ja|2月20日|12=draft|12=draft}}
* Spring Purification: Around {{ill|April 20|ja|4月20日|12=draft|12=draft}}
* Summer Purification (Oharai): Around {{ill|June 20|ja|6月20日|12=draft|12=draft}}
* Summer Kagura (festival): From {{ill|August 15|ja|8月15日|12=draft|12=draft}} to {{ill|August 16|ja|8月16日|12=draft|12=draft}}<ref>函館市史 銭亀沢編 p406-408</ref>

== Access ==
* {{ill|Nesaki Shrine Bus Stop|ja|根崎神社前停留所|12=draft|12=draft}} - Served by the {{ill|Hakodate Bus|ja|函館バス|12=draft|12=draft}} {{ill|Kaigan Line|ja|下海岸線|12=draft|12=draft}} (91, 91A, 91C routes)

